,Recommended,214730,14117967,"Posted: 22 January, 2015",all,Shymer,"Space Rangers 2 is a unique and improbable blend of space trading/fighting, robot-war based RTS and choose-your-own text adventures somewhat erratically translated from Russian. You play a Space Ranger trying to save the universe from the plague of a trio of evil AIs and the growing threat of pirates.Or not.You can ignore the story of the game and choose your own goal - and let the universe crumble around you. Sometimes you will be trading or running fedex missions between worlds. Sometimes releasing probes on unihabited worlds. Sometimes you will be jumping into a system infested with AI space vessels and trying to do your bit for the cause. Sometimes you will tracking down some rogue pilot for the money you need to buy your next ship. Sometimes you will be running a ski resort. Sometimes trying to get elected as president - or winning a Fonzer race - or just surviving prison as you wait for your release.If you can't imagine what that might be like, then you ought to try this game. It is a one-off.The pacing is all over the place. The turn-based space battles make mass combat a puzzle, rather than an adrenaline hit. Not a bad thing if you like that kind of thing. The planetary robot battles are long drawn out affairs of attrition rather than inspiration and the text adventures are... mixed... and involve a hell of a lot of reading and even more head scratching. But both are optional and feel almost like entire games all of their own. It can be hard to find your feet - the manual has vital information that the tutorial doesn't cover. It really is a bit of a stitched together monster.However to find all three genres in one game - and a game of so many options. Advancing tech tree - dynamic economy - an enemy expanding into your turf whether you like it or not - named competitors and rivals to fight, or hire. To have a story arc of a galactic battle against three baddies that you can choose whether to engage with - and how. And then to find you are a small cog in a vast machine of traders, pirates, military vessels and rangers who get on with their own lives with or without you. It's a glorious anarchic riot that has (either by luck or judgement) found a beautiful patchwork mix of the bizarre.For all of its faults - craziness - frustrations - iffy translations. It is, quite possibly, my favourite game."
