,Not Recommended,214730,35082441,Posted: 20 September,all,Cook,"Well, I've never been a fan of this game from the beginning and despite that, I managed to finish it a couple of times because the game had its own atmosphere. Of course, I'm talking aboutSpace Rangers 2: DominatorsandSpace Rangers 2: Reboot. But today I did not find the strength to waste more of my time on this version, and this is why:High grind which includes the constant completing of monotonous quests (not text quests) which are usually “go there and kill\deliver\find something” and not interesting space fights. Also, all of them have to be done in a limited time, so you have to check for yourself whether you can fly and complete the task on time and return back to get a reward.Lack of a convenient quest log. All that you have is a small panel at the bottom of the screen with pop-up windows. In addition, to find out where you need to go and what to do, you need to reread the unnecessary text. It would be much easier if instead of the text there was a brief description of the quest, as it was done with the information of who and were gave you this quest.Absurd dialogues which are written with a lot of Russian jargon, not funny jokes and old memes. Quite often I met dialogs that I think were written by a person who just wanted to joke but did not know how. And with each new version of the game, the number of these dialogues only increased. And finally, in this version, you can find old memes, which few people will know outside of Russia, right in the background. Why?!http://steamcommunity.com/sharedfiles/filedetails/?id=1139249326Lack of deep lore. Due to the fact that the dialogues were written by many different people for a long period of time, there is no one solid deep lore which gives some kind of uniqueness to the races. Honestly, i've got a strong filling that writers come up with dialogues at the time of writing, and not worked out them in advance.Of course, the game has positive aspects, such as complete freedom of action, a live and interactive world, a good trading system, interesting text quests (I'm talking only about those that were in Space Rangers 2: Dominators, I didn't play in new ones), ground battles, etc. But for me, inappropriate jokes and outdated memes of this version spoil the whole impression of the game.I wish that the game were more serious and also that the developers hired professional writers, instead of a bunch of fans with a questionable sense of humor.This version was developed primarily by fans of the game and is based on a free fan-made mod calledSpace Rangers 2: Revolution. So personally I will stick with the original Space Rangers 2: Dominators (even with Reboot version) without any questionable additions and gameplay changes.http://steamcommunity.com/sharedfiles/filedetails/?id=1139811847P.S. Because of the conflict between the developers, the previous parts of the game (Space Rangers 1 and Space Rangers 2: Reboot) were removed from Steam."
76561197970663919,Not Recommended,214730,14484514,"Posted: 15 February, 2015",all,RasterOps,"While the Space Rangers series is fun and this episode can be... this episode offers little of value. This game-concept allows the player to become a pirate in opposition of the Coalition. If that is your thing, then you will most likely enjoy this game more than me. If you despise pirates then this game will infuriate you.Pirates arrrr over powered (OP) even on Normal difficulty.  Some have speculated that pirates have to pay for their repairs, equipment, missiles and MM's. Inconceivable! They rarely if ever pick up loot. They cannot possibly get enough from extortion. They always have the best equipment and MM's. And 9 times out of ten they are doped up, improving their mad skillz.It is possible to ignore pirates, allow them to conquer Coalition systems and then land on""their""planets. If your relations with them are good, then they will leave you alone... except for independents. And maybe that's how to be less frustrated.NewSo this episode added a new Race/Faction, the pirates, its HD... some new weapons (which pirates use effectively in packs), Steam achievements, supposedly some new quests and perhaps a few more things. The ship defense design was changed to segregate Energy, Fragmentation and Missile weapons. The lower the score the less damage your ship will take in that class, e.g. M:80%.Unfortunately, this is where the game becomes unbalanced. There is one hull class in the game that consistently has thelowestdefense scores, ergo the best defenses, the Dumbo class. Like it or not this is thesingle/solegoto choice for ship hulls.OldThe devs did not correct the:Superfluous grammar and typographical errors, e.g. It's not ""Sale"", it's ""Sell"".It may be HD, but the display area is the same.Cannot zoom in or out on the tactical map (system travel)The minimap is fixed. You can go beyond the edge of the system but you will not be able to see your location or other objects on the minimap.The equipment reliability system has not changed and this is thegreatest problemwith the series. It's not the poor equipment reliability that is so irksome; there are two in-game mechanics for controlling that. It's the exorbitant cost to repair that is so poorly designed andunbalanced. A design that relies entirely upon recovering and selling Dominator equipment to science stations (full value). If there were no doms, thenNO ONEcould afford to repair their equipment. The design is ludicrous, frustrating and very aggravating... in other wordsNOTfun! This problem is compounded when fighting pirates. They rarely drop anything of value and the overall effect is just to wear out your equipment. IMO they also don't pay for their repairs.All quest and related dialogs force you to find the destination in the text but readily remind you of the ""Customer"". A simple ""Destination/Target"" heading would have been nice.No turn management improvements, e.g. everything requires an entire day to complete, e.g. landing, taking off, jumping, etc. Days (the turn) could have been divided into, oh I don't know, hours and allow the turn to be stopped at any point. The turn/hour progress indicator could easily be shown on the HUD. And if the time requirement to jump is 12 hours then at least you won't have to just sit there and wait a full day for all those missiles to catch up and blast you to pieces.Jumping still requires the ship to travel to some obscure location at the edge of a system. For instance, if you are at the outer lower edge of a system, you may have to travel to the top edge to exit, etc. More often than not this behavior is senseless and annoying, especially when being chased by...Birthday gifts, etcetera, are scattered all over the galaxy. No easy way to collect them all. Attempting to manage this loose inventory consumes too much game time. Time that your enemy is using to their advantage.There were no improvements to the trade/mercantile system (it's not just overly simplistic but senseless and boring)The planets in the Sol system are orbiting in the wrong directionStations... they spend all that money to build them but can't afford to equip them?! This is supposedly left to the player... who can't afford to repair his own gear let alone another station.The pace is aggressively fast, unbalanced. There is no time to enjoy other aspects of the game like quests... let alone collecting gifts and selling. It's pretty tedious. The game can be fun but get it on""sale""at 50% or greater."
,Not Recommended,214730,16336326,"Posted: 12 June, 2015",all,John Hadley,"Space Rangers HD is a very niche open-world turn-based space trading and combat strategy game that I think many people will find rather frustrating.  The game is improperly balanced so that the player has a very narrow path to success and a steep learning curve.  There's a lot of different ships and parts you can use, but many of them seem not to be viable and will lead to your death.   Not enough firepower?  You die.  Not fast enough?  You die.  Not earning enough income to pay off pirates or repair your ship after fighting them?  You die.   Not enough fuel make a hyperspace jump to run away?  You die.  The learning curve and narrow path to success reminds me very much of the game X3: Terran Conflict, another more-complex open-world space trading and combat game which I would recommend over this.  If you are able to find the path to success then you may enjoy these games greatly, but if you fail to find it you will die again and again without making much progress and probably give up the games without experiencing what they have to offer.In this game you are supposed to try to control the pirate threat but you aren't powerful enough to kill pirates early in the game, only fast enough to chase them around and sustain a lot of damage fighting them only to have them land on a planet and fully repair their ship most of the time.  Before you know it the whole universe starts getting overrun by pirates and you have only been able to kill one or two strays.  You start to get jumped by more pirates than you can afford to pay off or hope to kill off, run out of money, then die.  Prepare to save and reload often in this game as that seems to be the main path to survival when you don't know what you may encounter before entering a black hole or a sector or taking a quest.  Death is going to find you, so be sure you have saved before that.Some of the planet battles in the game are difficult and frustrating and will require many restarts in some cases before you randomly end up with the right plan and conditions that will allow you to succeed.  You can skip them if you want to as the game does have an option to do that.There is some gaming population that will find games with narrow success conditions and an abundance of options, many of which are superfluous or serve to hide the narrow path to success fun to play.  These players enjoy overcoming difficulty and pride themselves in their ability to analyze a situation and find a way to succeed.  They will find the way to exploit weaknesses, recognize patterns, and filter out what doesn't lead to success.  They require a certain amount of failure to make victory worth achieving.  If all or even most players succeeded, then the challenge would not be great enough for them.  If this sounds like you, then you may enjoy this game.  If that doesn't sound fun to you, then you probably should pass on this one."
