76561197996972957,Not Recommended,214730,13666682,"Posted: 28 December, 2014",all,sir Evans,"3/5 and only get it if it is on sale.I have played this game before it went HD and I completed it without cheats back then.It was long and tedious.Seeing it on sale on Steam I thought to myself - gonna get it, gonna cheat it, gonna have fun again.And I would like to point this out now - I am all against multiplayer cheaters, skill is all that should matter.However I totally support cheating/modding in single player modes, because poeple should enjoy the game the way they like.Fancy hardcore mode with one life? Go for it. Fancy easy mode with uber-guns and steamrolling through hordes of enemies? Go for it.Above everything else, have fun playing the title.Nope, not here.Space Rangers is a very difficult game and very time consuming. Unfortunatelly quite imbalanced too.Any attempts at using build in cheats or cheat engine will flag your game as 'cheated' and you will get no achievements, no score ranking etc.Keeping that in mind (you might think it is not a big deal, after all) I have to warn you that by playing this game you are in for a quite of a boredom unless you get the mechanics right - and quite a lot of dying as well, so save often before engaging in space combat.Now onto review:Graphics: 3,5/5It is colourful, eye candy, outdated 2006 graphic style ported into 2013 that will wear you out quickly.Game is not bad looking and there are no graphical issues I can speak of, but it is missing the immersivenes of other space themed titles - colourful nebulas, detailed planets, cool ship graphics - it is not there, do not expect it, don't look for it, don't wait for it. What you see in your first system is all there is.What you see in your first land battle/black hole is also all there is.Gameplay 3/5Planetary quests are hand drawn, text based, old school adventures of choices. They are in some parts very random and you are advised to save prior to starting one. Some of these (like this game of one pawn against 4) require few tries to complete due to random AI movements. Others require you to familiarize with quest first in order to understand it's mechanics. (A warning. Don't dig down in sex-change quest for a Peleng IF you play as a Peleng).Planetary quests are the most difficult part of the game and the most enjoyable. Each is different and unique; this is the only part where Space Rangers really shines.The RTS battles are sometimes simply impossible to win (you will see) and require constant activity (non-stop production and attacking) and are very crappy, but they pay quite well.Space battles and generally things you do in space fall into 2 categories:- making money by scavenging stuff from space/planets, performing easy quests (package delivery, get a quick ship, get all those quests and earn tons of money), or by so called trading (use trading centers to figure out best deals)- running into or away from combat. This is where this game falls flat on it's face and moans in agony. You will need few deaths to get used to general turn-based combat system, targeting, and generally understanding why you do not do any damage.In difference to the original game there is this pirate faction added into the title, but they are just 'meh'.You can either bother yourself with antagonizing pirates (meaning, every system will have a hostile pirate fighters) or going against Coalition (meaning, every system will become hostile), which is just as stupid as it sounds.There is no storyline to speak of. You are a ranger, who wants to become THE Ranger, there are some evil guys (rouge machines) that will shoot you on sight, there are some good guys (basically anyone else) that you can interact with. You either destroy the evil ones (oddly, you can join them, but it is game over with some info that you destroyed good guys) or they destroy everyone else, plain and simple. No twist, no immersion, no nothing. Just us vs them.Unless you cheat in money(and you don't want to in HD edition, as mentioned), you will have to spend first few(or more) years of the game just getting enough to buy a decent ship and components (and by decent I mean the one that lets you fly through dominator's systems and live) and upgrade them with micromodules to the point of usefulness. The real game starts then (you will get a ton of exp/badges by the time you will be ready for combat) only for you to discover that either:- evil ones are too strong and you will have to reconquer dozen of systems (gets very boring very soon, especially since they fight back trying to instantly recapture the system) just to get a chance to get to their homeworlds and destroy bosses- they have been reduced to just a few systems and there is no one left to fight (game will end in next few years)Music 1/5I will give this poor rating for what have been done in HD edition.In original game, music was in .dat format, you could listen to it outside of the game and with some tinkering replace the few poor track with something better. This is no longer the case in HD edition - everything is packed into pkg file.Therefore you are forced to listen to few very good tracks and then be interrupted with few really, really crappy.There is simply nothing you can do with that, as touching game files is out of the question.It's either turning the music off altogether and playing it out of soundtrack (really, a soundtrack was added as a standalone?) or suffering it while you will be pulling your hairs out during some intense (and by that I mean hundreds of missiles aimed at you) space combat.It's 2014 and steam workshop is alive and kicking, yet devs of this game are becoming increasingly paranoid about anyone who buys their stuff actually trying to get more fun out of it by cheating/modding.As such I can't recommend HD edition to you.Get yourself SR2:Reboot, play it, cheat the most annoying parts of it (and there are many), have fun.You won't have much fun here, once you will understand how little profit you can make by trading/missions and see the price tag for decent equipment and how shockingly imbalanced SR really is. This game simply becomes a grind for gold way too soon and stays that way until almost the end.Also some difficulty settings are no longer available on start - they have been moved to 'advanced settings' and using them means your score will not be posted (WTF, really?!). Yes IT IS THAT STUPID AS IT SOUNDS!So in conclusion - there are other titles for you to play for 18€ that you will enjoy much better. This one is not worth that much money.For less than a 5€ however you might give it a go, just don't expect too much and you won't be disappointed.You are warned."
